 (2893,'Giuda',2152,3434,'Giuda','Giuda &egrave; inserito nel gruppo di Giovanni e Pietro, indietreggia e, puntando il gomito destro sul tavolo, crea uno spazio nel quale si inserisce il volto di Pietro.\r\nNella iconografia dell&#039;&quot;ultima cena&quot; il personaggio di Giuda &egrave; quasi sempre rappresentato senza aureola, i tratti del suo volto sono duri (naso aquilino) a evidenziare la malvagit&agrave; dell&rsquo;animo, spesso &egrave; rappresentato nella tipica fisionomia dell&rsquo;ebreo.\r\nTalvolta compare la borsa dei denari, oppure &egrave; ritratto nel momento in cui intinge nel piatto o riceve da Ges&ugrave; il boccone. Spesso risulta estraneo o separato dal gruppo degli apostoli, nel Quattrocento viene isolato.',10),
 (2894,'Disposizione degli apostoli',2152,3435,'Disposizione degli apostoli','I dodici apostoli, privi di aureola, sono disposti sullo stesso lato del tavolo di fronte allo spettatore divisi in gruppi di tre. La lettura delle figure pu&ograve; essere eseguita sia partendo dal centro, sia partendo dalle estremit&agrave; destra e sinistra. E&rsquo; evidente la simmetria non rigida, ma di bilanciamento delle masse. Ciascun apostolo possiede una precisa individualit&agrave;, riconoscibile nell&rsquo; attenta variazione delle posture, dei  gesti e del movimenti delle mani. \r\nNel primo gruppo, Matteo tende le braccia verso Cristo, ma il busto ed il viso sono rivolti all&#039;indietro verso Simone e Taddeo; Simone &egrave; rivolto verso Taddeo che ha le mani aperte verso l&#039;alto.\r\nNel secondo gruppo, Tommaso, con il dito alzato, si protende verso Cristo. Giacomo &egrave; seduto ed allarga le braccia. Filippo &egrave; in piedi, con le mani sul petto.\r\nNel terzo gruppo, Giovanni ascolta le parole che Pietro gli sussurra. Pietro ha in mano un coltello. Giuda ha il gomito destro appoggiato sul tavolo.  \r\nNel quarto gruppo, Bartolomeo poggia le mani sul tavolo e si tende verso Cristo. Giacomo Minore poggia una mano sul braccio di Andrea, e con l&#039;altra tocca la spalla di Pietro. Andrea sta fermo al suo posto e solleva in alto le mani, con i palmi rivolti all&#039;esterno.',7),
 (2895,'Inside the Theatre&#039;s Ruins',NULL,3436,'Inside the Theatre&#039;s Ruins','The theatre of Palmyra has a typical Roman architecture. Under the platform, the columns carry inscriptions with the names of the statues that once stood there: representations of dignitaries, including emperors, princes of Palmyra, magistrates, officials, high-ranking priests and caravan chiefs. The front scene represented the entrance to a palace, with a central royal door and another door on either side, topped with niches and a complex colonnade. The actors performed in front of these doors, there were dressing rooms on either side. Theatre shows are still organised in the theatre that can host up to 2000 spectators. ',4),
 (2896,'The Roman Age',2895,3437,'The Roman Age','The Romans came to Syria in 64 B.C. and the whole of Syria became part of the Roman Empire. Palmyra had great importance, because of its position: it was next to the Euphrates and the Persian Empire. It was on the borders and was of strategic importance to the Romans, who needed to defend themselves against the Persian Empire, especially under king Odenathus who was called &ldquo;the King of kings&rdquo; or the &ldquo;King of the Orient&rdquo; by the Romans. He fought many battles against the Persians in the second half of the 3rd century A.D.  ',1),
 (2897,'The Independence ',2895,3438,'The Independence ','Under King Odenathus, Palmyra became very rich and important. His wife, Zenobia, decided, after his assassination at Homs in 268 A.D., to make of Palmyra an independent kingdom. Queen Zenobia reformed her army with the local police and drove away the Romans from Syria. She sent her troops towards North and South, towards Anatolia and Aleppo. Her troops arrived as far as Egypt, even if they only remained there for three years. The independent kingdom of Palmyra lasted 5 years.',2),
 (2898,'The Agora (Forum)',NULL,3439,'The Agora (Forum)','The Roman forum (or Agora) of Palmyra is situated near the Roman theatre; it was a big, rectangular plaza, the hub of Palmyrean life. It was used for public speeches and as a market, where caravans unloaded their wares to sell them and buy others. It was here that the commercial code of Palmyra was found. Around the Agora can be seen the remains of the feast hall and the area where the caravans were hosted. ',5),
 (2899,'Zenobia in Power',2898,3440,'Zenobia in Power','In the years 250 &ndash; 260 A.D., Palmyra was ruled by King Odenathus. Zenobia was his beautiful and dark-skinned second wife, from a high-rank Palmyrean Aramaean family. Under the reign of Odenathus Palmyra was still under Roman rule. While Queen Zenobia insistently asked her husband to fight against the Romans and gain independence for Palmyra, he preferred to rule under their protection. Odenathus was killed in 268 A.D. in the city of Homs, situated 160 kilometres north of Damascus. When he died, his son was still very young and Zenobia became the queen of Palmyra. ',1),
 (2900,'The Queen&rsquo;s Personality ',2898,3441,'The Queen&rsquo;s Personality ','Zenobia had a strong personality. She loved history and philosophy. She spoke several languages, Aramaic &ndash; her native language &ndash;, Greek and Egyptian, and was very cultivated. She was held in high respect by the court and the army. She had a powerful personality, and was very skilled at governing.\r\n',2),
 (2901,'Zenobia, a Stern Queen ',2898,3442,'Zenobia, a Stern Queen ','There is a historically-documented story about Zenobia. Once, a merchant arrived in Palmyra without paying taxes and without showing all his goods. The authorities arrested him and took him to the royal palace. The Queen got very angry with him, as this represented a huge offence for Palmyra. She decided to punish him in front of everybody. She called all the merchants in the theatre, had him tied to a pole in the centre of the theatre, with a hungry lion ready to be released. The merchant was terrified and asked to be forgiven. The gates opened but, instead of the lion, two chickens were released. The queen said this time they were only chickens, but next time they would be lions. This story shows the force and mercy of the queen. ',3),
 (2902,'Zenobia&rsquo;s Kingdom ',2898,3443,'Zenobia&rsquo;s Kingdom ','Zenobia owed the success of her expansion to a well-organized army. During the rule of Odenathus, the army was supported by the Romans and was well-organized to fight against the Persians. When Odenathus died, Zenobia decided to expand southwards and northwards in order to dominate all the regions and the commercial roads in the area. It was not as easy to expand towards Egypt as towards Anatolia, but she counted on her army for expansion. The army was powerful enough to be able to fight the Romans and drive them out of Syria. ',4),
 (2903,'Zenobia&rsquo;s Imprisonment ',2898,3444,'Zenobia&rsquo;s Imprisonment ','Around 272 A.D., Emperor Aurelian entered Syria from the North. He encountered the Palmyrean army at Antioch and then went towards Homs, where a great battle was fought. Aurelian won the battle and surrounded the city of Palmyra. Zenobia managed to escape during the night and tried to get help from the Persians. In 272 A.D., the Romans captured her on the Euphrates and took her to Aurelian&rsquo;s tent. There is no historical evidence of her death. According to some sources, she committed suicide as she wore a ring containing poison. Other stories say that she was taken to Rome and died of cold. Other legends tell that she arrived at Tivoli where she lived for two more years before being buried there. ',5),
