 (4245,'Centralization',NULL,5031,'Centralization','The centralization process has often been identified with the French Revolution and Napoleon, but it was the merit of Alexis de Tocqueville (a French political thinker) to analyze the fact that this process of centralization was much older.\r\nFrance is certainly, by far, the State which has been most successfully centralized in Europe since the XVI-XVII century. It&rsquo;s not that other States have not tried to do the same, but the most successful centralization process has taken place in France. Spain or Great Britain, for example, have also tried (in different ways) to apply the same recipe.',1),
 (4246,'succeed',4245,5032,'Key succeed','By welfare state we mean state interventions on health services, education and towards indigence. The birth of the modern welfare state coincides with a progressive undertaking by the state of social functions in the fields of health, education and assistance. This happens when the traditional framework (also called Ancient Regime), which is characterised by a censual corporative system based society, ends. Before state interventions, there was already a network that supplied services. In the ancient regime society, there were charitable institutions that were endowed by bequests and donations, so that they had enough money to supply assistance.\r\nThere were social bodies of many different kinds, expressed by local communities or churches, whose nature was a mix between ecclesiastic world and assistance world.',3),
 (4249,'Resistance',NULL,5035,'Resistance against centralization','Even if France has been the most successful centralized state, there has been, in the peripheries, a strong resistance to this centralization process, which we can still detect today. The resistance to the centralization process in France took, during the XVII and XVIII century, the form of many social revolts, which were mainly farmers&rsquo; revolts. When the crop was really poor people had not enough to eat, and so there were hungers in the countryside, as it happened, for example, just before the French Revolution of 1789.',2),
 (4251,'Colbertism',4249,5037,'Colbertism','During the kingdom of Louis XIV the central government was trying to regulate everything: even how a piece of linen, an handkerchief, had to be made. The inspiration for this policy came from Colbert, who gave his name to &ldquo;Colbertism&rdquo;: it means a very strong State intervention in the economy. Looking at the original documents of that time, it is interesting to notice that there is a directive by the King, but again and again he has to come back to the question, because he complains that some regulations are \r\nnot implemented yet. So France is a very centralized country, but it&rsquo;s also a country were there is a lot of resistance against central rule.',2),
 (4252,'Obstacle',4249,5038,'Loi Le Chapellier','Partially in order to eliminate resistance to the State The very famous &ldquo;Loi Le Chapellier&rdquo; (the law inspired by Le Chapellier)  adopted by the new elected assembly in 1791, established that it was forbidden for people to group together and to act together, because, in this very Jacobin concept of the State, there are only individuals and the government, with nothing organized in between. \r\nalso because intermediate bodies (like ancient corporations, or the clergy, or the aristocrats, or the military orders, etc.), all these groups were resisting to reforms. ',4),
 (4253,'Division of power',NULL,5039,'Division of power','The French king was very powerful, and so was the French state. \r\nIn the rest of Europe, in general, the central power was not able to be so strong as in France. In many situations, the ruler could not affirm himself so much because the feudal system was still very powerful.',3),
 (4254,'England and Italy',4253,5040,'England and italy','In Great Britain, there was a progressive transfer of power from the feudal lords to the people&rsquo;s representatives. So, Great Britain developed a\r\nrepresentative (even if not yet a democratic) system quite early.\r\nAlso in Italy, a strong central power was missing. Italy was very much divided into small states, communal organizations and alike, and it was in fact a battlefield for the other Europeans states. And there was the Church, the Catholic Church, which was a transnational force, but which was preventing in a way the possibility for Italy to become a State.',1),
