 (4431,'Searching for Sasquatch',NULL,5238,'The Pacific Northwest Expedition','One of the most famous hunts for Bigfoot remains the Pacific Northwest Expedition which united some of the country&rsquo;s most dedicated Bigfoot researchers in the late 1950&rsquo;s and early &lsquo;60&rsquo;s.  The Expedition was notable- not because of the evidence it uncovered- but because of the relationships that were built or destroyed as a result of what occurred.\r\n',1),
 (4433,'Tom Slick',4431,5240,'Assembling the Search','The expedition was conceived by Texas millionaire Tom Slick in 1959 after the Patterson-Gimlin film was made in Bluff Creek, CA.  Slick assembled a search team, among them newspaper publisher John Green, animal tracker Robert Titmus and researcher Ren&eacute; Dahinden.\r\n\r\nIn December of 1959, Slick flew in a helicopter out to the search site in California and began the hunt.  Armed groups began roaming the forest, looking for signs of the beast.  Trouble was on the horizon, however.  Slick had underfunded the groups, most of whom were forced to use their own vehicles and had no high-tech equipment.  Internal dissent began to cause problems with the search itself, the clash of personalities making it difficult to achieve any actual searching.\r\n',2),
 (4434,'The Experience',4431,5241,'From one who was there','Of the experience, John Green later stated in the film Sasquatch Odyssey: &ldquo;People who are prepared to stand up against the entire continent and go looking for something that everyone else says doesn&rsquo;t exist have a tendency to be pigheaded.  And when you put several of them together and try to organize something, they all have their own ideas of what they should be doing.&rdquo; ',3),
