 (351,'Intoduction',4089,'Intoduction','The limestone massif where the Dead Cities stand is a strange and fascinating place: rolling hills, lots of brownish grey rocks everywhere and, in between, plots of land with carefully cultivated dark brown soil. This place, full of history, belongs to the region of Antioch, city which was the geographic, economic and religious centre of the area in the Byzantine era (4th &ndash; 7th century A.D.). In spring, this place has a special beauty, the land has been ploughed and looks almost black, flowers are blooming everywhere, the sky is clear blue, the horizon is far away. The roads are narrow and winding, but with very little traffic, so the journey is easy. And, suddenly, a Dead City appears around a curve&hellip; This network of Byzantine villages also called &ldquo;Dead Cities&rdquo; is actually one of the most extraordinary archaeological site in the world: no less than 700 villages or cities scattered over a land of about 100 kilometres by 20. About 60 of these &ldquo;Dead Cities&rdquo; still look like real villages: only the population is missing. <br />\r\n--------<br />\r\nThis application is part of the project &quot;Marketing Activities for the Promotion of Syrian Cultural Heritage&quot;, whose overall objective is to support the Syrian Ministry of Tourism and Culture in promoting Syria as a cultural tourist destination. <br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe texts are based on an interview to Archaeologist Amr al-Azm, former director of conservation for the Directorate General for Antiquities and Museums in Syria and current head of the Centre for Archaeological Research and Scientific Laboratories at Damascus University and to Jean Pierre Sodini, professor at the Universit&eacute; Paris I, Panth&eacute;on-Sorbonne and senior member of the Institut Universitaire de France. <br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe texts were revised and re-edited by Babelmed Association and the Politecnico di Milano&#039;s team. The development and implementation of the application were managed by HOC Laboratory (Politecnico di Milano).<br />\r\n','info',1),
